# GoCMS UI Assets And Styling

- Treat generated runtime JS, generated CSS, and generated template output as build artifacts; regenerate them through scripts instead of hand-editing.
- Keep UI8Kit runtime JS subsetted to the ARIA patterns actually rendered by the admin UI.
- Do not use full CDN bundles for app-level admin behavior.
- Admin JavaScript must be progressive enhancement; core authorization, validation, CSRF, and publish/plugin state must be enforced server-side.
- Use explicit static utility classes that pass ui8px policy; do not hide required classes in runtime-only strings or broad safelists.
- Use semantic token classes for reusable UI colors; avoid raw palette utilities such as `bg-blue-500`, `text-slate-700`, or `border-red-500`.
- Do not write custom CSS declarations in GoCMS app selectors. App-owned semantic classes MUST be composed with `@apply` only.
- Keep selector bodies reviewable: comments and `@apply` are allowed; raw declarations such as `width:`, `color:`, `background:`, `border:`, or `position:` are not allowed in app-owned CSS.
- Repeated utility compositions should become UI8Kit variants, local elements, local blocks, or reviewed semantic patterns.
- Conformance tests should use `data-gocms-*` markers and accessible roles/names, not visual class names.
